docs.abstract: The police in Louisville, Ky., fatally shot Ms. Taylor during a nighttime raid on her apartment. Prosecutors said officers had lied in order to obtain a search warrant for Ms. Taylor’s home.
docs.snippet: The police in Louisville, Ky., fatally shot Ms. Taylor during a nighttime raid on her apartment. Prosecutors said officers had lied in order to obtain a search warrant for Ms. Taylor’s home.
docs.lead_paragraph: More than two years after police officers killed Breonna Taylor during a late-night raid of her apartment in Louisville, Ky., the Justice Department announced a series of federal charges on Thursday against four of the officers involved in the operation that set off racial justice protests across the country.

headline.main: Federal Officials Charge Four Officers in Breonna Taylor Raid
headline.print_headline: 4 Officers Face Federal Charges In Taylor Killing

docs.abstract: The men were convicted of federal hate crimes after state murder convictions in 2021. Their lawyers tried without success to have part of their sentences served in federal prison.
docs.snippet: The men were convicted of federal hate crimes after state murder convictions in 2021. Their lawyers tried without success to have part of their sentences served in federal prison.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — Before the three men convicted of murdering Ahmaud Arbery were sentenced on Monday on federal hate crime charges, they asked a judge to consider not only the length of the sentences, but also the location, with one lawyer arguing that if her client went straight to Georgia’s dangerous state prison system, he would be subject to “vigilante justice.”

headline.main: Two in Arbery Case Sentenced Again to Life in Prison; Third Man Gets 35 Years
headline.print_headline: Two of Arbery’s Killers Get Federal Life Sentences; Third Gets 35 Years

docs.abstract: Kelly Goodlett, the former detective, pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy. She is the first officer to be convicted in the fatal police operation.
docs.snippet: Kelly Goodlett, the former detective, pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy. She is the first officer to be convicted in the fatal police operation.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOUISVILLE, Ky. — A former police detective admitted on Tuesday that she had helped mislead a judge into wrongly authorizing a raid of Breonna Taylor’s apartment in Louisville, Ky., setting in motion the nighttime operation in which the police fatally shot Ms. Taylor.

headline.main: Ex-Detective Admits Misleading Judge Who Approved Breonna Taylor Raid
headline.print_headline: Ex-Detective Admits  Conspiracy to Mislead Judge on Taylor Raid

docs.abstract: Kelly Goodlett, who helped apply for a warrant for the fatal raid, would be the first officer convicted in the case.
docs.snippet: Kelly Goodlett, who helped apply for a warrant for the fatal raid, would be the first officer convicted in the case.
docs.lead_paragraph: A police detective in Louisville, Ky., is expected to plead guilty to conspiring to mislead a judge in order to obtain a search warrant for Breonna Taylor’s home, a plea that would mark the first conviction of a police officer over the fatal raid more than two years ago.

headline.main: Detective Expected to Plead Guilty Over Warrant in Breonna Taylor Raid
headline.print_headline: Officer to Plead Guilty to False Claims in Obtaining Taylor Warrant

docs.abstract: When warrants are based on misstated evidence or outright lies, the consequences can be disastrous. Prosecutors say that’s what happened in Ms. Taylor’s case.
docs.snippet: When warrants are based on misstated evidence or outright lies, the consequences can be disastrous. Prosecutors say that’s what happened in Ms. Taylor’s case.
docs.lead_paragraph: On the day before police officers shot and killed Breonna Taylor in her apartment in Louisville, Ky., a detective tried to persuade a judge that a former boyfriend of Ms. Taylor’s could be using her home to stash money and drugs.

headline.main: Breonna Taylor Raid Puts Focus on Officers Who Lie for Search Warrants
headline.print_headline: Issue in Taylor Shooting: Were Lies Used to Get Search Warrant?

byline.original: By Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs and Serge F. Kovaleski

docs.abstract: Attorney General Merrick B. Garland said the four officers “violated federal civil rights laws, and that those violations resulted in Ms. Taylor’s death.”

docs.lead_paragraph: Attorney General Merrick B. Garland said the four officers “violated federal civil rights laws, and that those violations resulted in Ms. Taylor’s death.”

headline.main: Four Officers Face Federal Charges Related to Breonna Taylor Raid
